== 3.1 _Quotient Groups_
#line(length: 100% , stroke: 2pt) ///////////////////////////////
=== The Big picture: homomorphisms and Fibers
Imagine a homomorphism $phi: G -> H.$ This map "collapses" $G$ onto $H$ by identifying certain elements of $G$ that map to the same element in $H$. The preimage of each element in $H$ under $phi$ is called a *fiber*. These fibers partition $G$ into disjoint subsets. 

For $X_a$ the fiber over $a in H,$ and $X_b$ the fiber over $b in H,$ define their product as the fiber over $a b$:
$ X_a X_b = X_(a b). $
This new operation on the fibers turns the set of fibers into a group, called a *quotient group*.

=== Kernel and Cosets 
The most important fiber is that over the identity element $e_H$ in $H$. 
#defn[Kernel][
  If $phi: G -> H$ is a homomorphism, the *kernel* of $phi$ is the set of elements in $G$ that map to the identity $e_H$  in $H$: $ 
  ker(phi) = {g in G| phi(g) = e_H }. 
  $ 
]
The kernel is a subgroup of $G$, and it has a special structure as follows 
#prop[Let $phi: G-> H$ be a homomorphism. Then 

1. $phi(e_G) = phi(e_H).$
2. $phi(g^(-1)) = phi(g)^(-1) med forall g in G.$
3. $ker(phi) <= G.$
4. The image $im(phi)$ is a subgroup of $H.$  
  ][] 

Next, we define *cosets*, which are understood as neighboring copies of a subgroup within the larger group.

#defn[Coset][ For any subgroup $N <= G,$ and any element $g in G,$ the set $ 
g N = {g n | n in N} 
$ is called a *left coset* of $N$ in $G$. The element $g$ is called a *representative* of the coset $g N$. Similarly, $N g = {n g| n in N}$ is a right coset. 
  ]

A crucial link between fibers, kernels and cosets is established by the following proposition:

#prop[Let $phi: G -> H$ be a homomorphism and $K = ker(phi)$ be its kernel. Let $X$ be the fiber of $a in H$. For any $u in X$ (i.e. $phi(u)=a$ ), then
$X = u K = {u k| k in K}$ is a left coset of Kernel.     ][]

=== Normal Subgroups and Quotient Groups

The fibers of a homomorphism partition the group into cosets of the Kernel. The group of these cosets forms the *quotient group*.

#defn[Operation on Cosets][
  Let $K = ker(phi)$. The set of fibers is denoted by  $G slash K$. We define a kinary operation on $G slash K$ as follows: $ 
  (u K)(v K) = (u v) K, quad forall u K, v K in G slash K. 
  $ 
   
]
In the particular case where this operation is well-defined, i.e. for a different $u' , v', $ we still have $(u' v') K = (u v)K,$ we say that $K$ is a *normal subgroup* of $G$. 
#defn[Normal subgroup][
  a Subgroup $N$ of a group $G$ is called a *normal subgroup* if $forall g in G,$ and $n in N,$$ 
  g n g^(-1) in N quad <=> g N g^(-1) = N.
  $ Denote  this $N$  as $N lt.tri.eq G.$ The elements $g n g^(-1)$ is the *conjugate* of $n$ by $g$. 
      
]
It's clear that onjugating a normal subgroup by any element of the group leaves the subgroup unchanged.

It can be proven that a normal subgroup has several equivalent characterizations:
#theorem[Let $N <= G.$ The following are equivalent: $ 
1.& N lt.tri.eq G. \
2. &forall g in G, g N = N g.\ 
3. & (u n) (v m) N= (u v) N quad forall u,v in G, "and" forall n,m in N. \
4. & N = ker(phi) "for some homomorphism" phi.
$<thm.normal_subgroup> 
 ][]
This theorem is the cornerstone of the section. It tells us that the subgroups we can "quotient by" are precisely the normal subgroups, which are precisely the kernels of homomorphisms.

If $N lt.tri.eq G$, the set of left cosets of $N$ in $G$, denoted $G\/N$, forms a group under the operation $(u N)( v N) = (u v)N$.
A quotient group is then defined as follows

#defn[
Quotient Group][
  Let $N lt.tri.eq G$ be a normal subgroup. The *quotient group* $G slash N$ is the set of left cosets of $N$ in $G$ with the operation defined by $ 
  (u N)(v N) = (u v) N, quad forall u , v  in G . 
  $Its set-builder representation is thus $ 
  G slash N = { g N | g in G }
  $ 
  
]





== 3.2 _Cosets and Lagrange Theorem_
#line(length: 100% , stroke: 2pt) ///////////////////////////////
This section builds on homomorphisms and normal subgroups (Section 3.1) to explore cosets of a subgroup $H <= G$. Cosets provide a way to "slice" $G$ into equal-sized pieces, leading to powerful counting results. The main tool is Lagrange's Theorem, which relates subgroup orders to the group's order.

=== Cosets Partition the Group.
Recall, for any subgroup $H <= G$ and any element $g in G,$ the set $g H = {g h | h in H}$ is called a *left coset* of $H$ in $G$. These form a partition of $G.$

#prop[Let $G $ be a group and $H <= G$. THen there exists distinct elements $g_1, g_2, dots, g_k in G$ for some finite $k,$ such that: 
1. $ G = union.big_i g_i H $ (Cosets partition G, and their union covers G.)
2. $ g_i H inter g_j H = emptyset ,(i eq.not j) $  
3. $ |g H| = |H| forall g in G. $    ][]

Core Insight: Cosets are "translates" of $H$ that tile $G$ without overlap. The number $k$ of cosets is called the index of $H$ in $G$.


#defn[
  Index of a subgroup][
    The index of $H <= G$, denoted $|G:H|$. is the number of distinct left cosets of $H$ in $G$. ( the "size" of the quotient group).
    
    For finite $G, $ $ 
    |G:H| = frac(|G|,|H|). 
    $ 
         
]

Lagrange theorem then follows naturally from the properties of cosets:
#thm[Lagrange's Theorem :

  Let $G$ be a finite group and $H <= G$. Then $|H|$ divides $|G|$, i.e., $|G| = |H| dot |G : H|$.
][]

=== Main Corollaries
Lagrange's Theorem has immediate consequences for elements, small groups, and normality.

#cor("Order of an element divides group order.")[If $G$ is finite and $g in G,$ then $|g|$ divides $|G.$  ][Let $H<= G$ and $H = angle.l g angle.r $. Then $|H| = |g|$. By Lagrange, $|H|$ divides $|G|$, so $|g|$ divides $|G|.$       ]

#cor("Groups of prime order are cyclic.")[If $|G| = p$ is prime, then $G$ is cyclic, i.e., $G tilde.equiv Z_p$ ][ The subgroups are only ${e}$ (order 1) and $G$ itself (order $p$ ) both divides $p.$ Let $g in G \\{e}, angle.l g angle.r <= G, $ then by Lagrange theorem, $|g|$ divides $p,$ so $|g| = p.$ Thus $G = angle.l g angle.r tilde.eq Z_p $ is cyclic.       ]

#cor("Subgroups of index 2 are normal.")[If $H <= G$ with $|G:H| = 2,$ then $H lt.tri.eq G.$ ][ There are only two left cosets: $H$ and $g H$ for some $g in G \\ H.$ And only two right cosets $H, H g$. Since both left cosets and right cosets partition $G,$ they must match, i.e. $g H = H g (forall g in G.)$ Therefore by @thm.normal_subgroup, $H lt.tri.eq G$       ]



== 3.3 _The Isomorphism Theorems_
#line(length: 100% , stroke: 2pt) ///////////////////////////////
The Isomorphism Theorems formalize the relationship between homomorphisms, kernels, and quotient groups established in Sec 3.1. 

For purpose of exam, we focus on the First Isomorphism Theorem, while understanding the 3rd theorem statement. The 2nd and 4th are omitted (they are so hard!)

=== The First Isomorphism Theorem
The First isomorphism theorem states that if we map $G$ to $H$ via a homomorphism $phi$, then the image of $phi$ is isomorphic to the quotient of $G$ by the kernel of $phi$.  




